deck_excerpt:
Updated february 2022, Despia Darklord deck very consistent and fun to play
Decklist tried 200+ times
deck_description:
EDIT: I have done some changing so some of the card that I wrote could not be in the deck anymore The starters are Aluber, Jester of Despia and Indulged Darklord. With Aluber, if you don't already have the field spell (Despia, Theater of the Branded), you search for that, otherwise search for Branded Opening that let you search Dramaturge of Despia or, if you have high level fusion monster in the GY, Ad Libitum of Despia. Now, with the field spell, you can fusion summon using Aluber on the field and what you have in the hand. With Indulged Darklord you want to give to the opponent Darklord Ukoback, if you can't usually the best one to give is Darklord Superbia and you want to search for Darklord Mornigstar, if you  can fusion summon into The first Darklord to nuke the board or Darklord Ixchel to cycle the deck. Some nice interactions are:
  • you can use the darklord you give to the opponent for a fusion summon using super poly
  • the second effect of The first Darklord that let you special summon a fairy monster trigger  Aluber, Indulged, Ukoback, Superbia
  • the best card to discard with Ixchel effect are the two trap cards that you can later use from the GY without paying the activation cost
  • the effects that discard cards like super poly, branded opening, allure of darkness, all of them synergize with Despian of tragedy letting you search for a despia monster
  • with golden sarcophagus if you target Despian of tragedy you trigger it's effect letting you search a despia monster and after 2 turn you take it into the hand (that's why i prefer it despite foolish burial, i found that the second effect to retrieve a speel is not that useful and i can still use it later sending Despian of tragedy to the GY with another card)
  • Darklord Superbia sometims miss timing so i reccomend to summon it at the end of a chain or outside of it
I don't like using card outside the archetype so I put staple cards in the side deck. It's very easy to summon rank 8 xyz monster and I decided to use N.38 and N.90 to cover the negating effect that the deck lacks. N.97 can be used as a finisher summoning N.100 that go easily at 9000 atk. The deck has a lot other synergies and interactions so I reccomend to try it and have fun. The deck is very very consistent and you have a dead hand 1/10 of the games, probably even less. Feel free to comment if you have any advice to improve the decklist.

deck_excerpt: Don't underestimate the power of the Nimble archetype!
deck_description:
This is good for Xyz and Link summoning high beatstick monsters using Nimble-archetype monsters.
  • Summon Nimble Beaver then special summon Nimble Musasabi to Xyz or Link summon depending on the situation.
    • If your opponent has a face-up or set spell/trap card, Link summon Knightmare Phoenix to destroy a set/face-up spell/trap card.
    • If your opponent controls a high beatstick monster that cannot be destroyed by battle, Xyz summon Sky Cavalry Centaurea, attack your opponent monster, then after the damage step, detach 1 xyz material from Centaurea to bounce your opponent's monster to their hand.
    • If your opponent controls a high beatstick monster, Xyz summon Number 64: Ronin Raccoon Sandayu, detach 1 material to special summon 1 Kagemusha Raccoon Token (its ATK becomes equal to the highest ATK monster on the field.), then the token attacks the opponent monster.
    • Optional summons: Missus Radiant, Mistar Boy, Masquerena and Relinquished Anima.
  • If Nimble Sunfish is destroyed by battle, send Nimble Angler to the graveyard to trigger its effect (Nimble Angler's effect: When this monster is send from hand or deck to the GY, special summon 2 Nimble monsters from your deck to the field except Nimble Angler), then trigger Sunfish's effect special summon 1 Nimble Sunfish to field from your deck. Now, there are 3 monsters on the field. You can:
    • Xyz summon Paleozoic Anomalocaris (3 materials or more) for high beatstick and immunity from card effects.
    • Xyz summon Number 29: Mannequin Cat (2 materials only), activate its effect to detach 1 monster, target 1 monster on your opponent's GY and special summon it to his/her field then target 1 monster from your opponent's field and special summon 1 monster of the same type or attribute as the target monster. Now you have a total of 3 monsters again on your field (1 Mannequin, 1 monster and 1 new special summoned monster). You can use these monsters to Link summon (it's up to you if you want to link summon or not.)
  • If Nimble Musasabi was destroyed by your opponent and he/she has 3 or more monsters and have either 1 or 2 monster zones available, special summon 2 Musasabi on his/her side of the field then activate Nibiru, the Primal Being quick effect to tribute all your opponent's monster to special summon 1 Primal Being Token to your opponent's field and stop them from their combo summons.
  • Super-Nimble Mega Hamster has the same method as Nimble Beaver but it takes longer to do some Xyz or Link summoning.
  • Obedience Schooled is good during your first turn or when you don't have any monster on your side of the field because you can summon 3 level 2 beast monsters with different names which is a good setup for Xyz summoning Mannequin Cat, Centaurea, and Sandayu which are beast-type monsters.
  • Bubble Bringer stops level 4 or higher monster from attacking and also, you send this card to the GY to special summon 2 level 3 or lower WATER monsters from the GY to the field to use as a Xyz or Link summon material.
Icejade Sharks (Nov 2021)

deck_excerpt: A powerful magical musketeer deck mixed with amazement and dogmatika engine. Better go first to play control with lots of interruptions. On the other
deck_description:
As usual magical musketeer deck, normal summon magical musketeer monster and try to annoy your opponent with your interruptions.

Infinite Impermanence can do trigger effect of Alerkino to special summon himself from hand and even if already have an Amaze Attraction Horror House, there can be a flip face-down and a monster effect negation.

Flexible in choosing magical musket cards to beat your opponent's cards. If go first with Nadir Servant, send Wind Pegasus @Ignister, add Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous so you have 1 interruption and also 1 powerful card to play in the next turn. Better caught with instant fusion when go second and special summon 1 of the "eyes restrict" depending on situations. Can use any link 2 monsters else in alternative to Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous. Cuz Magical Musketeer Max can special summon many monster in the same time, the 2 boss monster,Accesscode Talker is really a powerful monster to beat your opponent and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World can be used to beat your opponent boss monster, or archetypes using graveyard and even don't let your opponent play with I:P Masquerena using its effect to special summon this boss in your opponent turn. "Exchange" can be a cool card to use as you will know what deck your opponent uses and even take their handtraps to go against him/her and also trigger magical musketeer monster effect. As the reprint of dogmatika in the mega tin 2021, the dogmatika engine is more accessible. The Borrelsword Dragon be a cheaper card to use instead of Accesscode Talker . Finally, with many back-ups and flexibilties in situations, this mixed deck is pretty cool and can even beat meta decks if using interruptions effectively. Willing to improve this deck so feel free to make comments.

deck_excerpt: Pure Exorsisters Deck. Summon your XYZ monsters to punish your opponent for using their graveyard!
deck_description:
This is my current work-in-progress pure Exorsister deck.

My build here is a lot more slower-paced compared to some other Exorsister lists. Instead of turboing out Mikhaelise to search Vadis, I opted to run more traps and sit on main deck monsters.

 

The Game Plan:

Summon the main deck Exorsisters to try to proc them on your opponent's turn and utilize traps to interrupt your opponent's plays.

 

My thoughts on plays:

I normally don't really like summoning Mikhaelise turn 1, opting instead to just keep the main deck monsters on the field, but Mikahelise turn 1 is definitely not a bad idea. Depending on the matchup and your opening hand, Mikhaelise turn 1 can help shape your board around the opponent and round out your plays. However, the deck is not all Exorsister. This deck runs some traps to help back up your sisters. This deck runs Traptrick to help turbo out sisters using Vadis, but it could also search out other traps in case you open Vadis or search it with Mikhaelise. IDP is great against some decks and if used properly can end turns. Imperm is nice because it can be a hand trap and a normal trap. Speaking of hand traps, this deck also runs Dimension Shifter. Dimension Shifter on its own can also end turns. If you open Dimension Shifter turn 1, you can just normal summon a main deck sister to keep Dimension Shifter active.

 

Some of my card choices explained:

Some things I think this deck struggles with are hand advantage and finishing games.

When you're playing this deck, you often have to vomit out your hand. It feels almost like BA to me, except without the Cir-Dante loop. To combat this, I decided to add desires.

As for finishing games, it's a bit hard to link climb, and Vadis locks you into sisters, so I chose to run utopia the double, which does have some conflict with desires. Until I think of a better finisher, this is what I'll stick to.

I've also been thinking of messing with all of the sister ratios some more. I was originally running 3 of all the main deck sisters, but I felt like Elaine just wasn't doing much, so I decided to cut it to 2 for another copy of a trap. The ratios I have feel pretty good because you want to see at least one every turn. But I might experiment with it some more especially if I implement other engines.

 

My Thoughts

Overall, I've been having a lot of fun with Exorsisters. They're not the most competitive deck, but they are a lot of fun to play. Specifically, I love Carpedibel, their in-archetype prohibition. It just feels super rewarding to use. I'm thinking of experimenting with some other engines as well. I've seen some Magistus, Brave Token, and other builds that seem fun.

 

Please let me know if you have any thoughts or changes! Also, The side deck doesn't have much thought put into it, it's just some random stuff I threw in there.

deck_name: Red-Eyes Black Dragon + Mirror Force Dragon
deck_excerpt: This is a combination of Red-Eyes Black Dragon AND Mirror Force Dragon, because I thought the two go together. Remove it if you like, it won't hurt an
deck_description:
This deck contains the usual Red-Eyes cards as well as the materials needed to summon Mirror Force Dragon- possibly the worst things to put in one of these decks.

 

Using Insight, you can send one Red-Eyes and add one Spirit to your hand. You set spirit and chain it when you can- except to a Raigeki or other cards that remove your monsters.

You can use Cards of the Red Stone to get a pot of greed AND allow for one more use of the aforementioned Insight.

You can also use the XYZ monster to really quickly fill up the board- one Red-Eyes per turn. The turn you activate it- 2800 [from the XYZ monster] plus 2400 [from the Red-Eyes you summon by detaching material] = 5200 attack total. The next turn you add 2400 [from another detach] making it 7600 ATK. Over the 2 turns you deal over 12,000 ATK, and is enough to kill the player from full LP. All you need is 2 Red-Eyes monsters.

 

You can easily get Red-Eyes Alternative by discarding one Red-Eyes, or even the Alternative.

There are many more combos but these are the ones that come to mind.

deck_excerpt: Ideia diferente e massa pra jogar de Megálito (Megalith)
deck_description:
E aí, pessoal. Tudo certo? Espero que sim.

Hoje eu venho abordar minhas experimentações com Megalindos (English: "Megalith"/ Português BR: "Megálitos"), "Diabretiço" ( English: "Impcantation") e as "Artes de Ritual Superior e Avançada" (English: "High/Advanced Ritual Art"). Antes vou introduzir um pouquinho sobre a jogabilidade base dos "Megálitos". Se você não estiver interessado ou se já souber tudo sobre o arquétipo, fique à vontade para pular essa parte.

Introdução

"Megálito" é um arquétipo de Monstros Rituais do tipo Rocha com atributo TERRA e que se destacam por não terem uma magia ritual própria. Ao invés disso, os próprios monstros do arquétipo substituem as Magias Rituais, o que é ótimo por reduzirem 1 ⁄ 3 os requisitos para uma Invocação Ritual.

Todos os membros do arquétipo tem o efeito de se invocar por Invocação Ritual entre si, além de um efeito particular de cada monstro. Eles podem ser separados em 3 grupos de acordo com seu LV e função na estratégia.

Grupo 1: Monstros de LV 8 (parte agressiva/defensiva)

Esse grupo tem a função de invocar os Monstros Rituais "Megálito" da mão, ao se enviarem como custo e tributando monstros cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior do que o LV do monstro a ser invocado. Tenha em mente que, infelizmente, o monstro enviado para o GY e que está invocando outro por Invocação Ritual não têm seu LV contado para a soma, apesar de enviá-los ainda ser o custo do efeito de invocar. Além do efeito de Invocação Ritual, cada um deles têm efeitos diferentes quando em campo. Ambos os efeitos de cada monstro são Hard Once Per Turn. São eles:

"Aratron": este serve como uma hand trap durante a Fase Principal, pois seu efeito de invocar 1 monstro "Megálito" da mão é um Efeito Rápido. Isso é ótimo porque: 1. Você pode pegar seu oponente de surpresa, destruindo o campo do seu oponente com "Bethor" no turno 1 do oponente; 2. Te permite esquivar de efeitos que dão alvo nos seus monstros, fazendo os efeitos deles passarem mesmo tomando "Impermanência Infinita" ("Infinite Impermanence''), por exemplo. Seu outro efeito, em campo, é: "Quando seu oponente ativar um card ou efeito que dê alvo em um card que você controla (Efeito Rápido): você pode colocar um Monstro Ritual do seu GY no fundo do Deck; negue a ativação, e se isso acontecer, destrua-o." Eu acho muito feio quem roda menos que 3 em qualquer decklist;

"Bethor": "Se for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode dar alvo em cards que seu oponente controla até o número de Monstros Rituais com nomes diferentes no GY; destrua-os". Ótima carta, mas, apesar do potencial, você precisa preparar seu campo e GY para fazer bom uso dele. Eu gosto de rodar 2, mas não julgo quem roda menos que isso;

"Phaleg": é o powerhouse do Deck. Enquanto ele estiver em campo, todos os seus monstros ganham 300 ATK/DEF para cada Monstro Ritual no GY. Não é raro você ficar com 3 ou 4 monstros com mais de 2500 de ATK quando ele entra em jogo. Mesma coisa que "Bethor", eu gosto de rodar 2, mas também não julgo quem roda menos que isso.

Grupo 2: Monstros de LV 4 (buscadores/extendedores)

Todos eles têm um efeito de invocar 1 Monstro Ritual da mão ao tributar monstros, incluindo eles mesmos, cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior do que o LV do monstro a ser invocado. Esse efeito é hard once per turn. E cada um deles têm um efeito ao serem invocados por Invocação Ritual, e esses não são hard once per turn.

"Ophiel": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode adicionar 1 monstro "Megálito" do seu Deck à mão". Buscador que busca quantas vezes você puder invocar ele no mesmo turno. Preciso falar que é 3 no Deck? Preciso, né? Roda 3.

"Hagith": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode adicionar 1 card de Magia/Armadilha "Megálito" do Deck à mão". Buscador de backrow. Esse Deck ama backrow, mas não o suficiente para 3 Hagith. Eu gosto de usar só 1 porque o que não falta é jeito de buscar ou reciclar ele nesse deck.

"Och": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode comprar 1 card e descartar 1 card". Mas esse não é o talento dele. Ele se diferencia dos outros LV 4 porque pode invocar da mão qualquer Monstro Ritual em Velocidade de Magia 2. É por causa desse carinha que a galera gosta tanto de rodar "Shinobarão Pavão" ("Shinobaron Peacock"). Roda de preferência 1 pelo mesmo motivo que o "Hagith".

Grupo 3: "Phul", o Foda

"Megálito Phul" é um Monstro Ritual de nível 2 que "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode dar alvo em 1 Monstro Ritual no seu GY; o seu LV se torna igual ao alvo e depois adicione o alvo à mão". Além disso, "Durante a Fase Principal (Efeito Rápido): você pode ativar este efeito; Invoque 1 Monstro Ritual "Megálito" da sua mão ou deck tributando monstros da mão e/ou campo cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior que o LV do monstro invocado". Ele busca, recicla e pode interromper o turno do oponente. Só seria melhor se desse um impeachment no Salnorabo. Se puder, roda 5.

O Problema do Deck

O problema é que os Monstros Rituais do arquétipo necessários para começar a invocar outros monstros são de nível 8, ou seja, não podem ser buscados com "Preparação de Rituais" (English: "Preparation of Rites"), muito menos por "Pré-Preparação de Rituais" (English: "Pre-Preparation of Rites"), o que reduz muito a consistência necessária para fazer o que o Deck deveria fazer. O arquétipo conta com alternativas de busca, por meio dos monstros de LV 4 e LV 2, mas que, para buscarem, precisam ser invocados por Invocação Ritual (｡ŏ﹏ŏ). O Deck também conta com uma Magia Rápida que invoca por Invocação Ritual 1 "Megálito" direto do deck, que, por ser uma Magia Rápida, também não pode usufruir de suportes genéricos de Rituais, dependendo, assim, dos meios do próprio Deck.

 Aí entram os "Diabretiços", que não só aumentam a consistência do Deck, buscando as cartas Rituais chaves do Deck, mas também gera monstros para tributar para Invocações Ritual, sem falar nos combos com "Soberano da Vaidade" ("Vanity's Ruler") e o "Zaborg o Mega Monarca" ("Zaborg the Mega Monarch"). Só que "Megálito", por não ter Magias de Rituais próprias, deixa embaçado para usar o "Velaneco" ("Impcantation Candoll") e o "Livropedra" ("Impcantation Brookstone"), restando praticamente metade da engine.

Fora tudo isso, eu me canso fácil quando diferentes Decks, por terem a mesma engine ("Nekroz", "Shinobird", etc.), acabam ficando repetitivos e, por fim, enjoativo para a minha gameplay. Por isso eu tento misturar com outras engines para variar, por exemplo, trocar os "Diabretiços" por "Dogmatikas" ao jogar de "Nekroz".

Daí eu comecei a gastar massa cinzenta para deixar o "Megálito'' mais diferente de outros Decks que rodam a mesma engine.

Então, depois de gastar muito ATP e horas de experimentação, acabei com a seguinte lista. Vamos abordar o que têm de diferença de outras builds comuns de "Megálitos''.

"Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis" ("Blue-Eyes White Dragon") e "Dragão de Alexandrita" ("Alexandrite Dragon"): alvo para as "Artes de Ritual'' para trazer os monstros dos dois grupos. A escolha desses dois monstros se dá principalmente pelo LV 4 e 8, e também por terem a capacidade máxima de ATK dentre os vanillas.

"Arte de Ritual Avançada": ajuda bastante a pôr os primeiros monstros em campo sem gastar muito esforço, por enviarem os tributos do Deck. Te ajuda, também, a economizar os Rituais de LV 8 para que você possa usá-los de forma mais agressiva. E, por último mas não menos importante, você tem mais alvos para "Velaneco" e "Livropedra", deixando eles mais viáveis e o Deck mais consistente. Esse último argumento também serve para a "Arte de Ritual Superior".

"Arte de Ritual Superior": Traz Monstros do Deck. Ótimo para trazer os LVs 4 pro campo e realizar as buscas e ótimo também para deixar os LVs 8 também mais acessíveis.

Conclusão

Acredito que tenha resolvido os problemas do Deck que apontei anteriormente por meio dessas ações. Não tenho nada contra as engines genéricas, tanto que até continuei as utilizando. Só acho que quando roda o "Soberano da Vaidade"/"Mega Zaborg" fica meio repetitivo e reduz a versatilidade do Deck, deixando a condição de vitória dependente de poucas cartas que não são tão acessíveis o tempo todo.

Apesar disso tudo, não acho que ele tenha ficado OP Tier 0 1 card combo, mas acredito que desse jeito seja a forma mais divertida e consistente que você pode esperar desse Deck até então.

Valeuzão! Espero ter ajudado! E até a próxima ideia… ...se pá

Cosmic Dragons Strategy

The best opening hand consists of Doppelwarrior, Junk Converter, and any Tuner monster. First, activate Junk Converter's effect to discard itself and a tuner in your hand and add Junk Synchron to your hand (if you already have Junk Synchron, you can add Jet Synchron to your hand ) Normal Summon Junk Synchron, then use its effect to Special Summon Junk Converter from GY, and Special Summon Doppelwarrior from your hand. Synchro Summon Junk Speeder to EMZ using Junk Synchron and Junk Converter. Cl 1 Junk Speeder cl 2 Junk Converter. Special Summon Junk Synchron from GY and Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron, Jet Synchron. Synchro Summon Red Supernova Dragon to EMZ using Junk Speeder, Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron (If you have Jet Synchron in your hand, Special Summon it using Fleur Synchron's effect). Synchro Summon Martial Metal Marcher using Jet Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl 1 Martial Metal Marcher cl 2 Doppelwarrior. Special Summon 2 Tokens and Junk Syncchron from GY. Activate Jet Synchron's effect to bring it back from GY (if you already have a Jet Synchron on the field, then Cl1 Martial Metal Marcher Cl2 Jet Synchron to search Junk Synchron from Deck Cl3 Doppelwarrior). Synchro Summon Celestial Double Star Shaman using Jet Synchron and a Token. Use Celestial Double Star Shaman's effect to Special Summon Doppelwarrior from GY. Synchro Summon T.G. Hyper Librarian using Celestial Double Star Shaman, Doppelwarrior, a Token. Use Doppelwarrior's effect, Summon 2 Tokens. Synchro Summon Herald of the Arc Light using Junk Synchron and a Token. Synchro Summon Cosmic Blazar Dragon using Martial Metal Marcher, Herald of the Arc Light, T.G. Hyper Librarian. So your end board consist of a monster that can nuke your opponent board, a omni negate and a Lv1 token to Synchro Summon in your next turn. There is another way to end in the exactly same board. If you manage to have Junk Synchron, Doppelwarrior on your field and Jet Synchron in your hand, you can Synchro Summon Junk Speeder using Junk Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl1 Junk Speeder Cl2 Doppelwarrior, Summon 2 Tokens and Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron from your Deck. Synchro Summon Red Supernova Dragon to EMZ using Junk Speeder, Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron. Special Summon Jet Synchron from your hand using Fleur Synchron's effect. Synchro Summon Celestial Double Star Shaman using a token and Jet Synchron. Cl1 Celestial Double Star Shaman Cl2 Jet Synchron. Add Junk Converter to your hand, Special Summon Doppelwarrior from GY and Junk Converter from your hand. Synchro Summon T.G. Hyper Librarian using Celestial Double Star Shaman, Junk Converter and a token. Special Summon Jet Synchron from GY using Junk Converter. Synchro Summon Martial Metal Marcher using Jet Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl1 T.G. Hyper Librarian Cl2 Martial Metal Marcher Cl3 Doppelwarrior. Summon 2 tokens, Special Summon Junk Synchron from GY. Synchro Summon Herald of the Arc Light using Junk Synchron and a token. Synchro Summon Cosmic Blazar Dragon using Martial Metal Marcher, Herald of the Arc Light, T.G. Hyper Librarian.

Hello there, this is my new attempt on the Majespecter archetype. It is more of a "pure" version of the deck and I think this way, it is much stronger! Strategy The Strat is simple, set scales, pendulum summon as much as you can, search for traps and stop your opponent from playing Yu-Gi-OH! !! Turn three, you try to otk with Number S39: Utopia the Lightning. (that is also your plan going second) Card highlights Antihuman Intelligence ME-PSY-YA - ME-PSY-YA is a very powerful new pendulum card. It is a generic low scale with no restrictions, but an interesting floodgate effect. It banishes all spell and trap cards that would go to the GY while placed in the pendulum zone. This effect helps against decks that rely on floating or recycling spell and trap cards like Sky Striker and Eldlich. ME-PSY-YA' monster effect is quite strong as well, but not too important for this deck. Its main purpose is to be a low scale for the deck. Saambell the Star Bonder - While Saambell is not as strong as I initially believed, it is shares the same type and attribute as the Majespectors. It is a target for Ties of the Brethren and helps to go into Totem Bird, thanks to it being level three. Servant of Endymion - Servant's only purpose is to be a low scale for the deck while also being a target for Ties of the Brethren. Together with Spell Power Mastery, I play three copies of it. Secret Village of the Spellcasters - Village is a difficult one. I have seen many deck lists maining Village. The problem I see is that the Majespecters are getting tributed from the field to activate their traps and spells, eventually leaving you with no spellcasters on the field, resulting in Village to lock you down and not your opponent. Maybe I am too paranoid in that regard. It is still a strong floodgate against certain decks, so I decided to play it in the side deck.   The side deck presents some accountable options, but can be customized at will. Suggestions to improve the deck are welcome. :) Have a nice day, everyone!

deck_excerpt: Evil Eyes for the October 2021 format
deck_description:
Evil Eyes are actually lowkey kind of a good strategy when you cut out the filler. At the very least it has potential, I actually like the synergies between it an Eldlich. But ultimately I think a purer version of the deck can still compete. Don't get me wrong, there are reasons the deck is underexplored, and it probably won't be a tier 1 strategy any time soon, but the core of the deck is really good. You Normal Summon Serziel, then turn his ability on with Evil Eye of Selene, giving you one pop on an opponent's turn and a boss monster with great protection. This 1 card 1 interruption schtick has proven to be good enough in the past, and having other useful spells and traps to search if you see the Evil Eye of Selene is pretty boss too. In addition, it has a Field Spell that searches it.

So, when building an Evil Eye deck you have to consider which element to build around, are you a more "combo"ish Zerziel Turbo or are you Serziel Stun. The elements for both of these are okay. I ultimately decided on playing a very small Evil Eye package featuring none of the extra-deck monsters. I think this plays to Serziel's strengths better than playing the more comboish version, and I discovered this when melding the engine with Eldlich. You don't actually need to play a lot of Evil Eye cards outside of the core engine, the combos you are giving up aren't good enough, whereas Serziel by itself if at the very least close. My thought was to make this a dumb trap deck - summon Serziel, set 4 backrow is the nuts in this deck.

So, I started with tech cards. I'm not sure I'll stick to this system, but for now deciding on Tech Cards first is something I'm adopting into my deckbuilding process. This allows me to figure out what interactions I am playing ahead of my engine, so that I'm less inclined to "cut" tech cards in my deckbuilding process. Solemn Judgement IMO is obligatory in this type of deck - if you're playing a trap deck Lightning Storm and Evenly Matched and even Twin Twisters will ruin your day if you don't run this card. It could easily be in the side for games 2 and 3 but I like the card and it is a staple in my decks, because it is so versatile and powerful. Solemn Strike was added in the same breath, it's just a strong versatile card that is great going first and still very good going second, and a staple in successful Trap decks. Next I wanted a little spice. 2 Dogmatika Punishment made a lot of sense to me, but I wanted to run Trap Trick for essentially extra copies of this. With Trap Trick you're effectively running 4 Dogmatika Punishment for some purposes, but won't mind seeing the two of them together. For hand Traps I'm running 3 Imperm and 3 Dimension Shifter. Imperm is high enough impact, and doubles as a useful spell for Trap Trick to set, that it is worth running. D Shifter is potentially huge, we don't really play the GY game in this version of the deck and D Shifter is such a high impact hand trap that it is absolutely worth maining in basically any deck that can run it. Then I'm running 2 Evil Eye Retribution. You need at least 1 copy of this for when you see Evil Eye of Selene, but I think 2 gives us 5 cards Lightning Storm which is huge IMO. It also can't be negated if you have Evil Eye of Selene equipped to Serziel, though the downside is it does nothing if you don't see a Serziel. Evil Eye Defeat is also a huge interaction card, basically a 2 for 1 if you're strategy is online. We would only run 1 of these for the purposes of searching, but we need 2 to be able to use this off of Trap Trick. This way Trap Trick should almost always have something to set (and usually activate on resolution).

The next step was to throw in my Pot cards. As I said, you really need to see Serziel for the deck to do its thing, and the fact that it can play Prosperity and Duality for free is actually a huge upside for the deck. The pots don't even conflict, it is so insane.

After that it is 3 of the Field Spell with Terraforming, 3 Serziel, and 1 Evil Eye of Selene, your brick or Taketemborg for the engine. Evil Eye of Selene can reset itself, , so I think 1 copy of it is fine. It does leave you a little more vulnerable to Twin Twisters, but not by much. The Field Spell is always better to see than Serziel himself, since when Serziel pops you own card you can give up the Field Spell instead of something valuable. Regardless, I think you need all 7 copies of Serziel to play the Evil Eye engine. Sadly, you really don't need much else.

That left 6 spots in the deck, which was just perfect. I wanted to run packages of Floodgates that combo together, and to avoid bricking I thought packages of 2 made a lot of sense. So from just having put in everything I wanted I had the exact room to put in 2 Rivalry, the weakest floodgate but meta relevant and combos with There Can Be Only One, There Can Be Only One, the strongest individual floodgate that again combos with Rivalry of Warlords, and Summon Limit, which doesn't directly combo with either but puts a second limitation on opponents that combined with the first will frustrate them. These also have the advantage of being continuous spells, meaning you can pop them with Evil Eye cards after they've already done their job.

Punishment really didn't jive with the D Shifter in the deck, so it got cut for an Artifact Package. What is nice is that popping these cards yourself with Serziel lets you pop another card, so even if Scythe is dead Sanctum still puts in work in this deck. Scythe is also just really good, and is even half-decent to set a lot of the time.

In tuning I settled on a second copy of Selene because while it can be bricky, seeing it is nice, and it gives the deck a backup plan if your first is banished. I actually basically did what I always do and rebuilt the deck from the bottom up again, this time incorporating a couple copies of Zombie World. This card is decent as a floodgate in it's own right right now, but is notable for combing with Rivalry and There Can Be Only One very effectively. The idea is to have floodgates that are good on their own, but also combo with each other, and Zombie World fits that bill right now. The other notable new inclusion is 2 copies of crackdown. Much as I love the artifact engine in Evil Eye, when you only have 2 spaces to fill Crackdown is notable for stealing an opponent's monster to pop once it's on your side of the field, and means we might actually use our extra deck when our floodgates will let us. I still think 5 spell/trap negates is plenty, since when you see 1 of your copies of Selene you can search Retribution.

deck_excerpt: A deck that utilizes the power of Calculator and Gren Maju with the help of the Shiranuis.
deck_description:
The goal of this deck is to summon either Gren Maju Da Eiza or Calculator and make both of them gain tremendous ATK and DEF points with the help of Shiranuis. Shiranuis are good at swarming and banishing themselves out of the play to activate their innate effects. They can also return either to the field, GY or deck with the help of their support cards. Gren Maju Strategy: Using the effects of Dimensional Fissure, Pot of Desires, Pot of Extravagance, Golden Castle of Stromberg, Pot of Prosperity, Shiranui Style Samsara, Shiranui Squiresaga and Shiranui Samurai, this will increase Gren Maju Da Eiza's ATK and DEF dramatically. (possible ATK/DEF gain: 20,000+) Tips:
  • Pot of Desires is good if you already have Gren Maju during your first 5 draws. You can just banish cards without worry. It is best paired during the first draw with anti-summon, anti-spells/traps and anti-monster effect cards like Solemns, Ash Blossom and Ice Dragon's Prison.
  • If you don't have Gren Maju during your first 5 draws, swarm the field with Shiranuis and use them as a material to link summon Shiranui Skillsaga Supremacy which has a beneficial effect for FIRE monsters in which they can't be destroyed by battle. With this, once you summon Gren Maju, it will not be destroyed by battle and you can use cards that can banish other cards freely.
Calculator Strategy: By swarming the field with high level Shiranui Synchro monsters, you can dramatically increase Calculator's ATK. (possible ATK gain: 11,400. This is the sum of all Shiranui Synchro Monsters except 1 Shiranui Samuraisaga just to have a space for calculator to be summoned.) Tips:
  • Prevent Calculator's destruction by using your anti-magic/trap/summon/monster effect cards.
